The defendant Carrie E Counihan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Business Setting <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).
  • Theft-Business Setting <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).
  • Theft-Business Setting <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).

  • Theft-Business Setting <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Attorney Shane Laughton Brabazon in court. Colleen Catherine Nordin appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Annemarie Case appeared by phone for Auto Owner's Insurance Company. Court reviews motion, relief requested by Defendant. Defense requests additional time to correct motion filed pro se by Defendant, requests scheduling conference. State will be objecting to motion, presents argument in favor of scheduling conference, advises that it's difficult to respond to motion as written. Court makes statement, questions what type of schedule if being requested. Defense requests until 9/5 to file amended Motion. State has no objection. Court grants Defense until 9/5 to file Motion and supporting briefs. State has until 9/19 to respond. Defense has until 9/26 to reply. Atty Case questions whether she will need to call in for that date, would be asking Court to convert restitution to civil judgment if funds bounce. Court advises that sentence has been stayed, advises of objection by Atty Wimberger to entry of civil judgment. Further discussion regarding restitution issue. Court advises Atty Case to take appropriate measures to bring matter before the court, if necessary.  Oral ruling scheduled for September 28, 2017 at 09:00 am.

Defendant Carrie E Counihan in court with attorney Eric Richard Wimberger. Raymond Pelrine appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court questions status. Defense thinks Count 1 is ambiguous, has several hundred pages of receipts and credit cards statements to sift through, requests additional status date. Defense thinks case will get bogged down due to business documents. Court advises of retirement, scheduling issues, suggests reserve judge may have to be appointed, could set case as #2 in February. State advises there have been no conversations with Defense, has no idea what Defense/Defendant are planning to do. Further discussion regarding scheduling issue, reserve judge. Defense makes statement regarding computer backup, requests that records be kept beyond January 16. State requests that request be put in writing. Discussion regarding backup.
